We were happy to go down this road hand in hand with the Commission, even though this was not always characterised by complete harmony.
The profound reform of the Communityâs foreign policy that we are debating today cannot be considered in isolation from the upgrading of Parliamentâs role, which is long overdue, for we, considering the extent of the European Unionâs activities as a global player, are no longer prepared to stand looking over the fence while the governments take the decisions; on the contrary, we want to get actively involved in taking them.

It is for that reason that I have included in this report on the stability instrument a proposal for the introduction of a call-back procedure, which is intended to allow us in this House to bring politically irresponsible measures to a halt at the planning stage.
As I see it, there is a correlation between our increased activity in the sphere of foreign policy and the need for Parliament to have a greater say.
I want to emphasise once more that Europeâs 450 million citizens expect this democratic legitimacy, and expect it to be monitored.
